      "source": [
        "## 5. Introduction to the `super()` Function\n",
        "\n",
        "The `super()` built-in function in Python provides a way to access the methods and attributes of a parent class (or sibling classes in multiple inheritance) from a child class. It returns a temporary object of the superclass, allowing you to call its methods.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Syntax:**"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "5122dbd0"
      },
      "source": [
        "# This cell is for demonstrating the syntax of super().\n",
        "# It is not meant to be executed directly as ChildClassName and self are not defined here.\n",
        "# super(ChildClassName, self).method_name(arguments)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Example of how you would use it within a class:\n",
        "class Parent:\n",
        "    def greet(self):\n",
        "        print(\"Hello from Parent\")\n",
        "\n",
        "class Child(Parent):\n",
        "    def say_hello(self):\n",
        "        # Using super() without arguments in Python 3+ is equivalent\n",
        "        # to super(Child, self)\n",
        "        super().greet()\n",
        "\n",
        "# To avoid the NameError, this cell will not execute the problematic line.\n",
        "# The concept is explained in the markdown above and demonstrated in subsequent examples."
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "a6a62601"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 6. Using `super()` to Call Parent Constructors (`__init__`)\n",
        "\n",
        "The most common use case for `super()` is in the `__init__` method of a child class to call the `__init__` method of its parent class. This ensures that the parent class's attributes are properly initialized.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example 4: Calling Parent `__init__` with `super()`**"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "095b60f8",
        "outputId": "07806754-a327-41d0-e80a-bf00014443c4"
      },
      "source": [
        "class Person:\n",
        "    def __init__(self, name, age):\n",
        "        self.name = name\n",
        "        self.age = age\n",
        "        print(f\"Person object initialized: {self.name}, {self.age}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "class Employee(Person):\n",
        "    def __init__(self, name, age, employee_id, department):\n",
        "        # Call the parent class's __init__ method using super()\n",
        "        super().__init__(name, age)\n",
        "        # Initialize child class specific attributes\n",
        "        self.employee_id = employee_id\n",
        "        self.department = department\n",
        "        print(f\"Employee object initialized: {self.employee_id}, {self.department}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create an instance of the Employee class\n",
        "employee1 = Employee(\"Alice\", 30, \"E123\", \"Sales\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Access attributes from both parent and child classes\n",
        "print(f\"Name: {employee1.name}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Age: {employee1.age}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Employee ID: {employee1.employee_id}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Department: {employee1.department}\")"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Person object initialized: Alice, 30\n",
            "Employee object initialized: E123, Sales\n",
            "Name: Alice\n",
            "Age: 30\n",
            "Employee ID: E123\n",
            "Department: Sales\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "4c20f732"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Explanation:**\n",
        "\n",
        "*   In `Employee.__init__`, `super().__init__(name, age)` calls the `Person.__init__` method. This initializes the `name` and `age` attributes within the `Employee` object as defined in the `Person` class.\n",
        "*   After calling the parent's constructor, the `Employee` constructor initializes its own specific attributes (`employee_id`, `department`)."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "b8763b27"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Example 5: Chaining Constructors in a Deeper Hierarchy**"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "04b30013",
        "outputId": "bdc01cfb-27da-48ee-fa0a-b475e32677ac"
      },
      "source": [
        "class Grandparent:\n",
        "    def __init__(self, value1):\n",
        "        self.value1 = value1\n",
        "        print(\"Grandparent initialized\")\n",
        "\n",
        "class Parent(Grandparent):\n",
        "    def __init__(self, value1, value2):\n",
        "        super().__init__(value1) # Call Grandparent's __init__\n",
        "        self.value2 = value2\n",
        "        print(\"Parent initialized\")\n",
        "\n",
        "class Child(Parent):\n",
        "    def __init__(self, value1, value2, value3):\n",
        "        super().__init__(value1, value2) # Call Parent's __init__\n",
        "        self.value3 = value3\n",
        "        print(\"Child initialized\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create an instance\n",
        "my_object = Child(10, 20, 30)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Access attributes from all levels\n",
        "print(f\"Value 1: {my_object.value1}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Value 2: {my_object.value2}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Value 3: {my_object.value3}\")"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Grandparent initialized\n",
            "Parent initialized\n",
            "Child initialized\n",
            "Value 1: 10\n",
            "Value 2: 20\n",
            "Value 3: 30\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "7b0d1332"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Explanation:**\n",
        "\n",
        "*   When `Child(10, 20, 30)` is created, the `Child.__init__` is called.\n",
        "*   `super().__init__(value1, value2)` in `Child` calls `Parent.__init__`.\n",
        "*   `super().__init__(value1)` in `Parent` calls `Grandparent.__init__`.\n",
        "*   This demonstrates how `super()` allows for chaining constructor calls up the inheritance hierarchy."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "b045d8ae"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 7. Using `super()` to Call Overridden Parent Methods\n",
        "\n",
        "Sometimes, when you override a method in a child class, you still want to execute the original method from the parent class as part of the child's method implementation. `super()` allows you to do this. This is useful for adding functionality before or after the parent's method execution.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example 6: Extending Parent Method Functionality**"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "47bc2d9c",
        "outputId": "40af3341-9d8f-431e-f892-d4f6275af0d8"
      },
      "source": [
        "class Notifier:\n",
        "    def send_message(self, message):\n",
        "        print(f\"Base Notification: {message}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "class EmailNotifier(Notifier):\n",
        "    def send_message(self, message):\n",
        "        print(\"Preparing Email...\")\n",
        "        # Call the parent's send_message method using super()\n",
        "        super().send_message(message)\n",
        "        print(\"Email Sent.\")\n",
        "\n",
        "class SMSNotifier(Notifier):\n",
        "     def send_message(self, message):\n",
        "        print(\"Preparing SMS...\")\n",
        "        # Call the parent's send_message method using super()\n",
        "        super().send_message(message)\n",
        "        print(\"SMS Sent.\")\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create instances\n",
        "email_sender = EmailNotifier()\n",
        "sms_sender = SMSNotifier()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Send messages\n",
        "email_sender.send_message(\"Hello via Email!\")\n",
        "print(\"-\" * 20) # Separator\n",
        "sms_sender.send_message(\"Hello via SMS!\")"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Preparing Email...\n",
            "Base Notification: Hello via Email!\n",
            "Email Sent.\n",
            "--------------------\n",
            "Preparing SMS...\n",
            "Base Notification: Hello via SMS!\n",
            "SMS Sent.\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "b56a4327"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Explanation:**\n",
        "\n",
        "*   `EmailNotifier` and `SMSNotifier` override the `send_message` method from `Notifier`.\n",
        "*   Inside their overridden methods, they perform some specific actions (printing \"Preparing...\") and then call `super().send_message(message)` to execute the parent's original `send_message` logic.\n",
        "*   This allows them to add behavior while still utilizing the common notification logic from the base class."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "bc33d72c"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Example 7: Calling Parent Method Before and After Child's Logic**"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "4f822d0c",
        "outputId": "68ad663d-70c2-42d5-8a69-5ddc1d3b477a"
      },
      "source": [
        "class Task:\n",
        "    def execute(self):\n",
        "        print(\"Executing base task...\")\n",
        "\n",
        "class ComplexTask(Task):\n",
        "    def execute(self):\n",
        "        print(\"Starting complex task...\")\n",
        "        super().execute() # Call the parent's execute method\n",
        "        print(\"Complex task finished.\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create an instance and execute\n",
        "complex_task = ComplexTask()\n",
        "complex_task.execute()"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Starting complex task...\n",
            "Executing base task...\n",
            "Complex task finished.\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "e5eb1d2a"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Explanation:**\n",
        "\n",
        "*   The `ComplexTask`'s `execute` method adds steps before and after calling the `Task`'s `execute` method using `super()`."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "4c7a043a"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 8. Multiple Inheritance and the Method Resolution Order (MRO)\n",
        "\n",
        "Multiple inheritance is when a class inherits from more than one parent class. While powerful, it can introduce complexity, especially when parent classes have methods with the same name. Python uses the Method Resolution Order (MRO) to determine the order in which base classes are searched when looking for a method. The MRO follows a specific algorithm (C3 linearization).\n",
        "\n",
        "You can view the MRO of a class using the `.__mro__` attribute or the `help()` function.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example 8: Simple Multiple Inheritance**"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
