      "source": [
        "**Example 11: Using `super()` with Properties (Revisited and Corrected)**"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "c48b8e60",
        "outputId": "d36fd626-45cf-4900-f3f4-e28f6f63f3b0"
      },
      "source": [
        "class MyBase:\n",
        "    def __init__(self):\n",
        "        self._value = None\n",
        "\n",
        "    @property\n",
        "    def value(self):\n",
        "        print(\"Getting value from Base\")\n",
        "        return self._value\n",
        "\n",
        "    @value.setter\n",
        "    def value(self, new_value):\n",
        "        print(\"Setting value in Base\")\n",
        "        self._value = new_value\n",
        "\n",
        "class MyDerived(MyBase):\n",
        "    @property\n",
        "    def value(self):\n",
        "        print(\"Getting value from Derived\")\n",
        "        # Access parent's property getter using super()\n",
        "        return super().value + 10\n",
        "\n",
        "    @value.setter\n",
        "    def value(self, new_value):\n",
        "        print(\"Setting value in Derived\")\n",
        "        # Access parent's property setter - Note: Direct super().value = ... doesn't work for setters like this\n",
        "        # We need to call the underlying setter method of the parent property.\n",
        "        # One way is to access the property object from the parent class:\n",
        "        MyBase.value.__set__(self, new_value * 2)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create an instance\n",
        "derived_instance = MyDerived()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Set the value using the derived setter\n",
        "derived_instance.value = 5\n",
        "\n",
        "# Get the value using the derived getter\n",
        "print(f\"Final value: {derived_instance.value}\")"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Setting value in Derived\n",
            "Setting value in Base\n",
            "Getting value from Derived\n",
            "Getting value from Base\n",
            "Final value: 20\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "3c8eb569"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Explanation:**\n",
        "\n",
        "*   This example, revisited and corrected, shows how to interact with parent class properties using `super()`.\n",
        "*   In the getter, `super().value` works to call the parent's getter.\n",
        "*   In the setter, directly using `super().value = ...` is not the standard way to call the parent setter. The corrected approach involves accessing the parent property object and explicitly calling its `__set__` method."
      ]
    },
